\details{
tabular's package boundary is \strong{display-only}: pre-summarised
data in, rendered file out. \code{pivot_across()} is the canonical
bridge between the cards aggregation backend and that boundary.
It does not aggregate — it pivots arms to columns, interpolates
per-cell display strings from the stat values, and applies
decimal precision. Filtering, weighting, and aggregation happen
upstream in cards or your own data-prep step.
\subsection{Zero-suppression (always-on default)}{

A row whose \code{n} value equals zero renders the whole cell as the
bare \code{n} value instead of fully interpolating the format string.
For a categorical level with \code{n = 0}, the cell shows \code{"0"}, not
\code{"0 (0.0\%)"}. This is clinical convention — empty cells should
read as a single zero, not advertise a meaningless rate.

\strong{How the default fires (chain of events).} During cell assembly,
before format-string interpolation, the engine checks the row's
\code{n} stat. If it is zero, the engine short-circuits and returns the
formatted \code{n} value (\code{"0"}) as the entire cell — \code{{p}} is never
substituted, so the \verb{(0.0\%)} half of the format string is dropped.

\strong{How to opt out: supply a custom \code{fmt$n}.} Setting any function
under \code{fmt$n} is the engine's signal that the user owns the \code{n}
rendering. The short-circuit is disabled for the whole table; for
every row the full format string interpolates, so \code{{n}} becomes
your formatter's output and \code{{p}} becomes the standard percentage.
For \code{n = 0}, that's \code{"0 (0.0\%)"}.

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{# Force "0 (0.0\%)" for n = 0 rows by attaching a custom n formatter.
# The body of fmt$n can be the default integer rendering — its
# presence alone is what disables the zero-suppression branch.
pivot_across(
  saf_demo_card,
  statistic = list(
    continuous  = "\{mean\} (\{sd\})",
    categorical = "\{n\} (\{p\}\%)"
  ),
  fmt = list(n = function(x) sprintf("\%d", as.integer(x)))
)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Pharma rounding (always-on default)}{

A percentage that would otherwise round to \code{0} (when the value
is positive but smaller than the chosen precision) renders as
\verb{<0.1}; one that would round to \code{100} (positive but smaller than
100) renders as \verb{>99.9}. The threshold is precision-aware:
\code{decimals = c(p = 2)} produces \verb{<0.01} / \verb{>99.99}. This matches
the pharma convention of never claiming exactly \verb{0\%} or \verb{100\%}
when at least one subject contributed.

Override per-stat via \code{fmt}:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{# Show exact rounded percentages even at the extremes
pivot_across(
  data,
  statistic = "\{n\} (\{p\}\%)",
  decimals  = c(p = 1),
  fmt = list(p = function(x) sprintf("\%.1f", x * 100))
)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Your \code{fmt$p} receives the raw stat value (a proportion between
0 and 1) and returns the displayed string. The pharma-threshold
branch only fires inside the built-in \code{p} formatter and the
\code{decimals}-driven path, so any custom \code{fmt$p} bypasses it.
}
